# Git Command Line Practice and Repository Automation

## Introduction

This practice session focused on learning Git and GitHub operations completely through command line interface (CLI) without using manual GitHub options.

The main objective was to understand repository creation, file creation, version management, command line automation, and synchronization between local repository and remote GitHub repository.

All operations were performed using Git Bash on Windows.

---

## Task Assigned

The task assigned during mentoring session was:

1. Create **4 separate GitHub repositories** using command line only.

Repositories created:

```text
repo1-task
repo2-task
repo3-task
repo4-task
```

2. In each repository create **4 files**.

Files created in each repository:

```text
file1.txt
file2.txt
file3.txt
file4.txt
```

3. In every file add the following version variable:

```text
$MODULE_VERSION="1.2.1"
```

4. Push all repositories to GitHub using command line.

5. Change module version in all repositories:

```text
1.2.1 → 3.4.1
```

without manually editing files.

6. Show command history as proof of work.

---

## Step 1 : GitHub CLI Setup

GitHub CLI was installed and authenticated.

Commands used:

```bash
gh --version
gh auth login
gh auth status
```

Purpose:

* Connect GitHub account with terminal.
* Enable GitHub repository management from command line.

---

## Step 2 : Creating 4 GitHub Repositories

Repositories were created directly from terminal.

Commands used:

```bash
gh repo create repo1-task --public
gh repo create repo2-task --public
gh repo create repo3-task --public
gh repo create repo4-task --public
```

Purpose:

* Create repositories without manually clicking GitHub website.

Repositories created:

```text
repo1-task
repo2-task
repo3-task
repo4-task
```

---

## Step 3 : Cloning Repository To Local Machine

Repositories were downloaded to local system.

Commands used:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/username/repo1-task.git
git clone https://github.com/username/repo2-task.git
git clone https://github.com/username/repo3-task.git
git clone https://github.com/username/repo4-task.git
```

Purpose:

* Create local copy of remote GitHub repositories.

---

## Step 4 : Creating 4 Files In Repository

Inside every repository 4 files were created.

Command used:

```bash
touch file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt file4.txt
```

Files created:

```text
file1.txt
file2.txt
file3.txt
file4.txt
```

Purpose:

* Create files directly from terminal without manual creation.

---

## Step 5 : Writing Version Configuration In Files

The same module version was added inside every file.

Command used:

```bash
echo '$MODULE_VERSION="1.2.1"' > file1.txt
echo '$MODULE_VERSION="1.2.1"' > file2.txt
echo '$MODULE_VERSION="1.2.1"' > file3.txt
echo '$MODULE_VERSION="1.2.1"' > file4.txt
```

Output inside each file:

```text
$MODULE_VERSION="1.2.1"
```

Purpose:

* Store version configuration inside files.

---

## Step 6 : Git Workflow

After creating files, Git workflow was used.

Commands used:

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Added 4 files with module version 1.2.1"
git push origin main
```

Understanding:

```text
git add     → prepare changes

git commit  → save changes locally

git push    → upload changes to GitHub
```

Purpose:

* Save changes locally and upload to remote repository.

---

## Step 7 : Automating Repeated Work Using Loop

Instead of repeating commands manually for all repositories, shell loop was used.

Command used:

```bash
for repo in repo2-task repo3-task repo4-task
do
commands
done
```

Purpose:

* Automate repeated commands for multiple repositories.

Understanding:

```text
for  → repeat operation

do   → start execution

done → stop execution
```

---

## Step 8 : Changing Version Automatically

All file versions were changed automatically from:

```text
1.2.1
```

to

```text
3.4.1
```

Command used:

```bash
sed -i 's/1.2.1/3.4.1/g' *.txt
```

Purpose:

* Replace old version with new version automatically.

Understanding:

```text
sed = stream editor

-i  = edit file directly

s   = substitute

g   = replace globally
```

Result:

```text
$MODULE_VERSION="3.4.1"
```

---

## Step 9 : Manual File Version Change Practice

A single file was changed manually.

File used:

```text
file2.txt
```

Version changed:

```text
3.4.1 → 0.7.2
```

Command used:

```bash
sed -i 's/3.4.1/0.7.2/g' file2.txt
```

Purpose:

* Practice changing version in one file only.

Important learning:

Changing file locally does not update GitHub automatically.

Need:

```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Updated version"
git push origin main
```

---

## Step 10 : Viewing Command History

Command history was checked to verify all work done.

Commands used:

```bash
history
history | grep git
history | grep gh
```

Purpose:

* Show all commands executed during task.

